{"id":"type/article","type":"type","webTitle":"Article","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]},{"id":"publication/theguardian","type":"publication","sectionId":"theguardian","sectionName":"From the Guardian","webTitle":"The Guardian","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/all","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/publication/theguardian","references":[],"description":"All the latest from the world's leading liberal voice."},{"id":"theguardian/travel","type":"newspaper-book","sectionId":"travel","sectionName":"Travel","webTitle":"Travel","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/travel","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/theguardian/travel","references":[]},{"id":"theguardian/travel/travel","type":"newspaper-book-section","sectionId":"travel","sectionName":"Travel","webTitle":"Travel features","webUrl":"https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/travel/travel","apiUrl":"https://content.guardianapis.com/theguardian/travel/travel","references":[]}],"fields":{"headline":"Richard Grant's ideal US road trip","standfirst":"The long-term motor nomad and author of Ghost Riders explains what makes a road trip – from music and food to highways and backroads","trailText":"<p><strong>Richard Grant</strong>, long-term motor nomad and author of Ghost Riders, on what makes a road trip – from music and food to highways and backroads</p>","byline":"Richard Grant","main":"<figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-image-397644696\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Travel/Late_offers/pictures/2012/10/11/1349967122810/The-Grand-Canyons-South-R-002.jpg\" alt=\"The Grand Canyon's South Rim, Arizona\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">The Grand Canyon's South Rim, Arizona.  Photograph: Getty Images</span> </figcaption> </figure>","body":"<p>Let the dawn rise behind you, and drive on towards the sunset. The great American road trip goes west, not east, and it ends at the barrier of the Pacific Ocean. Westward like the pioneers, you travel through ever bigger, emptier and more dramatic landscapes. The skies get taller. The horizons stretch out. You reach the great national parks of the Rockies, where wolves and bears and something close to wilderness still exists, and drive on through the red rock canyonlands of Utah and Arizona.</p> <p>The worst mistake is to be in a hurry. The drive from New York to California is 2,800 miles if you make the mistake of taking the most direct route. If you loop and detour as you should, it&apos;s closer to 3,500 miles, and you want at least 10 days and preferably three weeks or more. Use the interstate highways when you have long stretches to cross, but be sure to meander down plenty of backroads.</p> <p>Unless you have the sort of personality that can&apos;t stand it any other way, keep the planning to a minimum. A cross-country road trip should be a loose, freewheeling, improvisational adventure, full of surprises and sudden friendships with extraordinary strangers.</p> <p>Bars are always good places to meet people. So are independent bookstores – where they survive. The staff invariably know the best places to eat and drink locally, and if there happens to be a cool band playing that night, or a wrestling contest in the back of a local feed store, they can usually tell you about that too. Be observant. America is a land of many signs and billboards, and this is how you&apos;ll find your way to, say, the World&apos;s Largest Prairie Dog, or a saloon called something like Bad Barb&apos;s Vapors.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-image-397644698\"> <img src=\"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Travel/Late_offers/pictures/2012/10/11/1349967311338/Richard-Grant-001.jpg\" alt=\"Richard Grant\" width=\"460\" height=\"277\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Richard Grant on the road</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>If a weird rock formation glimpsed off in the distance looks appealing, get yourself over there. A hummingbird might buzz your face; a coyote might trot past. Maybe you&apos;ll experience a moment of perfect silence, or run across an eccentric burying an old fridge full of modern artefacts as a time capsule for future archeologists.</p> <p>I used to go across the country with a change of clothes and a toothbrush, and sleep in the back of whatever shitheap car I had bought for the trip. These days I&apos;m not so pure. I like a dependable vehicle and I stay in motels until I reach the western deserts and mountains. Then I look for remote public land administered by the Bureau of Land Management (<a href=\"http://www.blm.gov/wo/st/en.html\" title=\"\">blm.gov/wo/st/en.html</a>) where I can camp for free and build a fire, usually without sticking to a designated area. I pack a sleeping bag and sometimes a tent, and I never get on the road without a camp stove, an espresso pot, and a pound or two of good ground coffee. Motel and gas station coffee is almost uniformly awful. A bottle of whiskey is a true friend if you find yourself in a dry county down south, and a gallon of water can quite literally save your life if you break down on a desert backroad in summer. I also pack a knife, fork, matches, can-opener and corkscrew, and a small grill to prop over a campfire.</p> <p>Gastronomic despair is a real possibility, especially on interstates. The same fast food restaurants cluster at every exit — Mickey-D&apos;s, Burger Thing, Junk In The Box, Pizza Butt, Dead Lobster and Taco Hell. There are now websites devoted to eating well across the country, and while I check them obsessively in gas stations and motels, the results are usually disappointing. The websites are crowd-sourced, which means that most of the reviewers don&apos;t know what they&apos;re talking about. <a href=\"http://chowhound.chow.com/boards\" title=\"\">Chowhound.com</a> is the best of them, but I&apos;d advise looking up the recommendations of top American food writers such as <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/2002/oct/13/foodanddrink.features5\" title=\"\">Jeffrey Steingarten</a> or Jonathan Gold.</p> <p>The most direct route across the US takes you through the flat cornfields of the Midwest, where American food, and arguably American culture, is at its least zesty. I advise a more southerly course, for the music and storytelling and because the south has barbecue. The meat, which is usually pork shoulder and ribs until you reach Texas, where it changes to beef brisket, is rubbed or marinated with spices and tenderisers, and then cooked slowly for many hours over woodsmoke in a pit or chamber. Hot damn! Done right, it&apos;s amazingly succulent and tangy, and there are dozens of regional variations. An Alabama prison guard once told me his favourite barbecue was &quot;so good it make you wanna hurt somebody!&quot;</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-image-397644699\"> <img src=\"https://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Travel/Late_offers/pictures/2012/10/11/1349967238887/Mississippi-Riverboat-001.jpg\" alt=\"Mississippi Riverboat\" width=\"460\" height=\"277\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">A riverboat on the Mississippi. Photograph: Getty Images</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Presumably, you will have supplied yourself with some suitable American music for the journey. If the blues sounds good in Clapham, try listening to Muddy Waters or Fred McDowell when driving through the swamps and cotton fields of the Mississippi delta. Better yet, stop off in a raw backcountry juke joint, buy a pint of moonshine from the man outside and hear the last surviving bluesmen playing it live. You will feel very foreign, but not unwelcome.</p> <p>Tom Waits has a knack for getting you through the last miles to a motel when you&apos;re dead tired. When you&apos;re driving through a thunderstorm at night on the high plains of Colorado, try Bob Dylan. Gram Parsons sounds just right in the desert, and so do the new tripped-out DJ sounds of Gonjasufi.</p> <p>The first time I drove across the country, I felt so liberated and happy – and so dejected when we reached the end of the road and stared out at the Pacific. So I drove back the other way to New Orleans, and then up to Montana, and down to Arizona. For a couple of years, I lived on the road, sleeping in cars and tents and other people&apos;s houses, doing odd jobs and pieces of journalism. You hear a lot of windy nonsense trumpeted about freedom in America, especially by politicians, but when you&apos;re roaming around the enormous public lands of the American west, sleeping next to a different campfire every night, you&apos;re about as free as you can realistically get in this day and age, and that&apos;s the best reason there is to hit the road.</p> <p><em>• Read more about Richard&apos;s travels at </em><a href=\"http://www.richardgrant.us/\" title=\"\"><em>richardgrant.us</em></a><em>. His classic book about crossing the US is Ghost Riders (Abacus £9.99). His latest book is Crazy River (Abacus £9.99). To buy a copy of either for £7.99 with free UK p&amp;p go to </em><a href=\"http://www.guardianbookshop.co.uk/BerteShopWeb/viewProduct.do?ISBN=9780349112688\" title=\"\"><em>guardianbookshop.co.uk</em></a><em> </em></p>","newspaperPageNumber":"2","wordcount":"1088","commentCloseDate":"2012-10-15T21:45:02Z","commentable":"true","creationDate":"2012-10-08T10:15:57Z","internalComposerCode":"56ab7215e4b00a5f2f008932","internalOctopusCode":"6747844","internalPageCode":"1811679","isPremoderated":"false","lastModified":"2012-10-12T11:39:21Z","newspaperEditionDate":"2012-10-13T00:00:00Z","productionOffice":"UK","publication":"The Guardian","shortUrl":"https://gu.com/p/3bx46","shouldHideAdverts":"false","showInRelatedContent":"true","legallyS